	<center>
	    <h3>
		Is a Point in a Box?
	    </h3>
	</center>
	<hr WIDTH="100%">
	<h2>Introduction:</h2>
	This lab exercises the ability to:
	<ul>
	    <li> Work with conditionals (<i>primary objective</i>) </li>
	    <li> Define and apply parameterized functions (<i>primary objective</i>) </li>
	    <li> Work with coordinate geometry (<i>secondary objective</i>) </li>
	</ul>
    <h2>Lab Assignment:</h2>

    <ol>
	<li> Create a new directory, <b><tt>Lab7</tt></b>, in your class account directory.</li> 
	<li> Move into your <tt>Lab7</tt> directory</li> 
	<li> Create the file <tt>pointInBox.html</tt>
	<li> Use HTML comments at the top of this file identifying:</li> 
	<ul> 
	    <li>where the file is located (e.g. <tt>~/cs200999/labs/Lab7/pointInBox.html</tt>)</li> 
	    <li>the author (<i>you</i>) </li> 
	    <li>what the program does</li> 
	    <li>when you created the file</li> 
	    <li>when you last modified the file</li> 
	</ul> 
	<li>When implementing your program, as often as is practical, repeat the following steps:</li> 
	<ol> 
	    <li> modify your Web page file via the editor</li> 
	    <li> save the file</li> 
	    <li> refresh the browser open to your Web page</li> 
	    <li> verify that your modifications did what you've intended</li> 
	</ol>
	<li> Determine whether a given point's ( <b><i>X</i></b>, <b><i>Y</i></b> ) coordinate pair is in a specified box area, using the following components:</li>
	<ul>
	    <li>Textboxes (<i>with default values</i>) for each of the [input] values of the box coordinates:
	    <b>Top, Bottom, Left, and Right.</b>
	    <li>Define, test, then use a <tt>function</tt> labeled <tt>IsPointInLineSegment()</tt> having the following properties:
	    <ul>
		<li>parameters:
		<ul>
		    <li><tt>leftBoundary</tt>
		    <li><tt>rightBoundary</tt>
		    <li><tt>point</tt>
		    <li>Boolean flag <tt>boundariesAreIn</tt>
			(will be <b><tt>true</tt></b> if the boundary points are considered part of the line segment)
		    <li><tt>orientationString</tt> (will be <tt>"Horizontal"</tt> or <tt>"Vertical"</tt> for a rectangle)
		</ul>
		<li>with the following functionality:
		<ul>
		    <li>if the <tt>leftBoundary</tt> is not less than the <tt>rightBoundary</tt>,
			raise an <tt><u>alert</u>()</tt> stating that the <tt>orientationString</tt> box coordinates are bad.
		    <li><tt>return</tt> 
		    <dl>
			<dt>
			    <b><tt>true</tt></b>
			<dd>
			<tt>If the <tt>point</tt> is <b>inside</b> the line segment</tt>
			<dt>
			    <b><tt>false</tt></b>
			<dd>
			<tt>If the <tt>point</tt> is <b>outside</b> the line segment</tt>
		    </dl>
		</ul>
	    </ul>
	    <li>Two labeled textboxes for the ( <b><i>X</i></b>, <b><i>Y</i></b> ) coordinates of the point, i.e.
	    a textbox for the <b><i>X</i></b> coordinate, and a textbox for the <b><i>Y</i></b> coordinate.
	    <li>A labeled button to <i>toggle</i> whether the box border is considered to be in the box. (<i>Establish and use a default value</i>)<br>
	    This button will toggle a Boolean <i>flag</i> variable. This button will also use a textbox to display one of the following two text strings (messages) on the page in a textbox:<br>
	    <dl>
		<dt>
		    <b><tt>true</tt></b>
		<dd>
		    <tt>The box border is <b>inside</b> the box.</tt>
		<dt>
		    <b><tt>false</tt></b>
		<dd>
		    <tt>The box border is <b>outside</b> the box.</tt>
	    </dl>
	    <li>Using the <tt>IsPointInLineSegment()</tt> function, implement:
	    <ul>
		<li>A button to test whether or not the point is in the box.
		<li>A textbox to display and state whether the point is in the box, e.g.:
		<dl>
		    <dt>
			<b><tt>true</tt></b>
		    <dd>
		    <tt>The point ( <b><i>X</i></b>, <b><i>Y</i></b> ) is <b>inside</b> the box.</tt>
		    <dt>
			<b><tt>false</tt></b>
		    <dd>
		    <tt>The point ( <b><i>X</i></b>, <b><i>Y</i></b> ) is <b>outside</b> the box.</tt>
		    <dd>
		    <br>(<b>note:</b> display the values of <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i>)
		</dl>
	    </ul>
	</ul>
	<li>Think about how you could modify and extend this program to determine whether a point
	( <b><i>X</i></b>, <b><i>Y</i></b>, <b><i>Z</i></b> ) is inside or outside a 3D box.
    </ol>

    <p>Label descriptively all boxes and buttons (an HTML <tt>&lt;table&gt;</tt> will be useful for this).
    <p><u>Test</u> your code.
    <p>Try to use <u>functions</u> to help organize and simplify your code.
    <p>When finished, submit to the dropbox.

